[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **cycle** in a graph is a non-empty trail in which only the first and last vertices are equal.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A **directed cycle** in a directed graph is a non-empty directed trail in which only the first and last vertices are equal.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A graph without cycles is called an *acyclic graph*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A directed graph without directed cycles is called a *directed acyclic graph*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A connected graph without cycles is called a *tree*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A chordless cycle in a graph, also called a hole or an induced cycle, is a cycle such that no two vertices of the cycle are connected by an edge that does not itself belong to the cycle.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] An antihole is the complement of a graph hole.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Chordless cycles may be used to characterize perfect graphs: by the strong perfect graph theorem, a graph is perfect if and only if none of its holes or antiholes have an odd number of vertices that is greater than three.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A chordal graph, a special type of perfect graph, has no holes of any size greater than three.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The girth of a graph is the length of its shortest cycle; this cycle is necessarily chordless.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Cages are defined as the smallest regular graphs with given combinations of degree and girth.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A peripheral cycle is a cycle in a graph with the property that every two edges not on the cycle can be connected by a path whose interior vertices avoid the cycle.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] In a graph that is not formed by adding one edge to a cycle, a peripheral cycle must be an induced cycle.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The term *cycle* may also refer to an element of the cycle space of a graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] There are many cycle spaces, one for each coefficient field or ring.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The most common is the *binary cycle space* (usually called simply the *cycle space*), which consists of the edge sets that have even degree at every vertex; it forms a vector space over the two-element field.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] By Veblen's theorem, every element of the cycle space may be formed as an edge-disjoint union of simple cycles.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A cycle basis of the graph is a set of simple cycles that forms a basis of the cycle space.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Using ideas from algebraic topology, the binary cycle space generalizes to vector spaces or modules over other rings such as the integers, rational or real numbers, etc.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The existence of a cycle in directed and undirected graphs can be determined by whether a depth-first search (DFS) finds an edge that points to an ancestor of the current vertex (i.e., it contains a back edge).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] All the back edges which DFS skips over are part of cycles.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] In an undirected graph, the edge to the parent of a node should not be counted as a back edge, but finding any other already visited vertex will indicate a back edge.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] In the case of undirected graphs, only *O*(*n*) time is required to find a cycle in an *n*-vertex graph, since at most *n* − 1 edges can be tree edges.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Many topological sorting algorithms will detect cycles too, since those are obstacles for topological order to exist.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Also, if a directed graph has been divided into strongly connected components, cycles only exist within the components and not between them, since cycles are strongly connected.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] For directed graphs, distributed message-based algorithms can be used.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] These algorithms rely on the idea that a message sent by a vertex in a cycle will come back to itself.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Distributed cycle detection algorithms are useful for processing large-scale graphs using a distributed graph processing system on a computer cluster (or supercomputer).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Applications of cycle detection include the use of wait-for graphs to detect deadlocks in concurrent systems.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] For undirected graphs, "neighbour" means all vertices connected to *v*, except for the one that recursively called *DFS(v)*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] This omission prevents the algorithm from finding a trivial cycle of the form *v*→*w*→*v*; these exist in every undirected graph with at least one edge.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A variant using breadth-first search instead will find a cycle of the smallest possible length.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The corresponding characterization for the existence of a closed walk visiting each edge exactly once in a directed graph is that the graph be strongly connected and have equal numbers of incoming and outgoing edges at each vertex.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] In either case, the resulting closed trail is known as an Eulerian trail.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] If a finite undirected graph has even degree at each of its vertices, regardless of whether it is connected, then it is possible to find a set of simple cycles that together cover each edge exactly once: this is Veblen's theorem.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] When a connected graph does not meet the conditions of Euler's theorem, a closed walk of minimum length covering each edge at least once can nevertheless be found in polynomial time by solving the route inspection problem.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The problem of finding a single simple cycle that covers each vertex exactly once, rather than covering the edges, is much harder.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Such a cycle is known as a Hamiltonian cycle, and determining whether it exists is NP-complete.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The cycle double cover conjecture states that, for every bridgeless graph, there exists a multiset of simple cycles that covers each edge of the graph exactly twice.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Proving that this is true (or finding a counterexample) remains an open problem.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Several important classes of graphs can be defined by or characterized by their cycles.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] In mathematics, computer science and digital electronics, a **dependency graph** is a directed graph representing dependencies of several objects towards each other.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] It is possible to derive an evaluation order or the absence of an evaluation order that respects the given dependencies from the dependency graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] Given a set of objects S and a transitive relation $R\subseteq S\times S$ with $(a,b)\in R$ modeling a dependency "*a* depends on *b*" ("*a* needs *b* evaluated first"), the dependency graph is a graph $G=(S,T)$ with $T\subseteq R$ the transitive reduction of *R*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] For example, assume a simple calculator.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] This calculator supports assignment of constant values to variables and assigning the sum of exactly two variables to a third variable.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] You can derive this relation directly: *A* depends on *B* and *C*, because you can add two variables if and only if you know the values of both variables.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] Thus, *B* must be calculated before *A* can be calculated.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] Since *B* depends on *D* to be calculated, *A* must also depend on *D* to be calculated before it (hence the transitive property stated above).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] On the other hand, the values of *C* and *D* are known immediately, because they are number literals.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] In a dependency graph, cycles of dependencies (also called **circular dependencies**) lead to a situation in which no valid evaluation order exists, because none of the objects in the cycle may be evaluated first.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] If a dependency graph does not have any circular dependencies, it forms a directed acyclic graph, and an evaluation order may be found by topological sorting.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] Most topological sorting algorithms are also capable of detecting cycles in their inputs; however, it may be desirable to perform cycle detection separately from topological sorting in order to provide appropriate handling for the detected cycles.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] Assume the simple calculator from before.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] The equation system "*A*=*B*; *B*=*D*+*C*; *C*=*D*+*A*; *D*=12;" contains a circular dependency formed by *A*, *B* and *C*, as *B* must be evaluated before *A*, *C* must be evaluated before *B*, and *A* must be evaluated before *C*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] A **correct evaluation order** is a numbering $n:S\rightarrow \mathbb {N}$ of the objects that form the nodes of the dependency graph so that the following equation holds: $n(a)<n(b)\Rightarrow (a,b)\notin R$ with $a,b\in S$ .
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] This means, if the numbering orders two elements a and b so that a will be evaluated before b , then a must not depend on b .
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] There can be more than one correct evaluation order.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] In fact, a correct numbering is a topological order, and any topological order is a correct numbering.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] Thus, any algorithm that derives a correct topological order derives a correct evaluation order.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] Assume the simple calculator from above once more.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] However, (*C*, *D*, *B*, *A*) is a correct evaluation order as well.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/dependency-graph] Then the string consisting of the vertex labels ordered by a correct evaluation order corresponds to a string of a trace.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] A version of depth-first search was investigated in the 19th century by French mathematician Charles Pierre Trémaux as a strategy for solving mazes.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] The time and space analysis of DFS differs according to its application area.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] In theoretical computer science, DFS is typically used to traverse an entire graph, and takes time $O(|V|+|E|)$ , where $|V|$ is the number of vertices and $|E|$ the number of edges.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] This is linear in the size of the graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] In these applications it also uses space $O(|V|)$ in the worst case to store the stack of vertices on the current search path as well as the set of already-visited vertices.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] Thus, in this setting, the time and space bounds are the same as for breadth-first search and the choice of which of these two algorithms to use depends less on their complexity and more on the different properties of the vertex orderings the two algorithms produce.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] For applications of DFS in relation to specific domains, such as searching for solutions in artificial intelligence or web-crawling, the graph to be traversed is often either too large to visit in its entirety or infinite (DFS may suffer from non-termination).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] In such cases, search is only performed to a limited depth; due to limited resources, such as memory or disk space, one typically does not use data structures to keep track of the set of all previously visited vertices.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] For such applications, DFS also lends itself much better to heuristic methods for choosing a likely-looking branch.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] When an appropriate depth limit is not known a priori, iterative deepening depth-first search applies DFS repeatedly with a sequence of increasing limits.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] In the artificial intelligence mode of analysis, with a branching factor greater than one, iterative deepening increases the running time by only a constant factor over the case in which the correct depth limit is known due to the geometric growth of the number of nodes per level.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] DFS may also be used to collect a sample of graph nodes.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] However, incomplete DFS, similarly to incomplete BFS, is biased towards nodes of high degree.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] The edges traversed in this search form a Trémaux tree, a structure with important applications in graph theory.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] Performing the same search without remembering previously visited nodes results in visiting the nodes in the order A, B, D, F, E, A, B, D, F, E, etc. forever, caught in the A, B, D, F, E cycle and never reaching C or G.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] Iterative deepening is one technique to avoid this infinite loop and would reach all nodes.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] The result of a depth-first search of a graph can be conveniently described in terms of a spanning tree of the vertices reached during the search.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] Based on this spanning tree, the edges of the original graph can be divided into three classes: **forward edges**, which point from a node of the tree to one of its descendants, **back edges**, which point from a node to one of its ancestors, and **cross edges**, which do neither.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] Sometimes **tree edges**, edges which belong to the spanning tree itself, are classified separately from forward edges.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] If the original graph is undirected then all of its edges are tree edges or back edges.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] It is also possible to use depth-first search to linearly order the vertices of a graph or tree.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] For binary trees there is additionally **in-ordering** and **reverse in-ordering**.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] For example, when searching the directed graph below beginning at node A, the sequence of traversals is either A B D B A C A or A C D C A B A (choosing to first visit B or C from A is up to the algorithm).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] Note that repeat visits in the form of backtracking to a node, to check if it has still unvisited neighbors, are included here (even if it is found to have none).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] Thus the possible preorderings are A B D C and A C D B, while the possible postorderings are D B C A and D C B A, and the possible reverse postorderings are A C B D and A B C D.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] Reverse postordering produces a topological sorting of any directed acyclic graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] This ordering is also useful in control-flow analysis as it often represents a natural linearization of the control flows.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] The graph above might represent the flow of control in the code fragment below, and it is natural to consider this code in the order A B C D or A C B D but not natural to use the order A B D C or A C D B.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] The recursive implementation will visit the nodes from the example graph in the following order: A, B, D, F, E, C, G.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] The non-recursive implementation will visit the nodes as: A, E, F, B, D, C, G.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] 2. it delays checking whether a vertex has been discovered until the vertex is popped from the stack rather than making this check before adding the vertex.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] If G is a tree, replacing the queue of the breadth-first search algorithm with a stack will yield a depth-first search algorithm.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] For general graphs, replacing the stack of the iterative depth-first search implementation with a queue would also produce a breadth-first search algorithm, although a somewhat nonstandard one.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] Another possible implementation of iterative depth-first search uses a stack of iterators of the list of neighbors of a node, instead of a stack of nodes.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] This yields the same traversal as recursive DFS.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] The computational complexity of DFS was investigated by John Reif.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] More precisely, given a graph G , let $O=(v_{1},\dots ,v_{n})$ be the ordering computed by the standard recursive DFS algorithm.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] This ordering is called the lexicographic depth-first search ordering.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] John Reif considered the complexity of computing the lexicographic depth-first search ordering, given a graph and a source.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] A decision version of the problem (testing whether some vertex u occurs before some vertex v in this order) is **P**-complete, meaning that it is "a nightmare for parallel processing".
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] A depth-first search ordering (not necessarily the lexicographic one), can be computed by a randomized parallel algorithm in the complexity class RNC.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/depth-first-search] As of 1997, it remained unknown whether a depth-first traversal could be constructed by a deterministic parallel algorithm, in the complexity class NC.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In mathematics, particularly graph theory, and computer science, a **directed acyclic graph** (**DAG**) is a directed graph with no directed cycles.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] That is, it consists of vertices and edges (also called *arcs*), with each edge directed from one vertex to another, such that following those directions will never form a closed loop.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is a DAG if and only if it can be topologically ordered, by arranging the vertices as a linear ordering that is consistent with all edge directions.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] DAGs have numerous scientific and computational applications, ranging from biology (evolution, family trees, epidemiology) to information science (citation networks) to computation (scheduling).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs are also called **acyclic directed graphs** or **acyclic digraphs**.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph is formed by vertices and by edges connecting pairs of vertices, where the vertices can be any kind of object that is connected in pairs by edges.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In the case of a directed graph, each edge has an orientation, from one vertex to another vertex.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A walk in a directed graph is a (finite or infinite) sequence $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc )$ of vertices such that each consecutive pair $(v_{i},v_{i+1})$ is connected by a directed edge.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A path is a walk where all vertices are distinct.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle is a walk $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc ,v_{n})$ where the only repeated vertex is $v_{n}=v_{1}$ , meaning the last vertex equals the first vertex.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph is a directed graph that has no cycles.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The reachability relation of a DAG can be formalized as a partial order ≤ on the vertices of the DAG.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In this partial order, two vertices u and v are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* exactly when there exists a directed path from u to v in the DAG; that is, when u can reach v (or v is reachable from u).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] However, different DAGs may give rise to the same reachability relation and the same partial order.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, a DAG with two edges *u* → *v* and *v* → *w* has the same reachability relation as the DAG with three edges *u* → *v*, *v* → *w*, and *u* → *w*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Both of these DAGs produce the same partial order, in which the vertices are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* ≤ *w*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a DAG is the graph with the most edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG, and may therefore be thought of as a direct translation of the reachability relation ≤ into graph-theoretic terms.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In this way, every finite partially ordered set can be represented as a DAG.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction of a DAG is the graph with the fewest edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the covering relation of the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] It is a subgraph of the DAG, formed by discarding the edges *u* → *v* for which the DAG also contains a longer directed path from u to v.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Like the transitive closure, the transitive reduction is uniquely defined for DAGs.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for a directed graph that is not acyclic, there can be more than one minimal subgraph with the same reachability relation.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Transitive reductions are useful in visualizing the partial orders they represent, because they have fewer edges than other graphs representing the same orders and therefore lead to simpler graph drawings.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A Hasse diagram of a partial order is a drawing of the transitive reduction in which the orientation of every edge is shown by placing the starting vertex of the edge in a lower position than its ending vertex.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] goes from earlier in the ordering (upper left) to later in the ordering (lower right).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is acyclic if and only if it has a topological ordering.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A topological ordering of a directed graph is an ordering of its vertices into a sequence, such that for every edge the start vertex of the edge occurs earlier in the sequence than the ending vertex of the edge.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph that has a topological ordering cannot have any cycles, because the edge into the earliest vertex of a cycle would have to be oriented the wrong way.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, every graph with a topological ordering is acyclic.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Conversely, every directed acyclic graph has at least one topological ordering.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The existence of a topological ordering can therefore be used as an equivalent definition of a directed acyclic graphs: they are exactly the graphs that have topological orderings.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, this ordering is not unique; a DAG has a unique topological ordering if and only if it has a directed path containing all the vertices, in which case the ordering is the same as the order in which the vertices appear in the path.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The family of topological orderings of a DAG is the same as the family of linear extensions of the reachability relation for the DAG, so any two graphs representing the same partial order have the same set of topological orders.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The graph enumeration problem of counting directed acyclic graphs was studied by Robinson (1973).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] (2004) proved, that the same numbers count the (0,1) matrices for which all eigenvalues are positive real numbers.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The proof is bijective: a matrix A is an adjacency matrix of a DAG if and only if *A* + *I* is a (0,1) matrix with all eigenvalues positive, where I denotes the identity matrix.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Because a DAG cannot have self-loops, its adjacency matrix must have a zero diagonal, so adding I preserves the property that all matrix coefficients are 0 or 1.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A *multitree* (also called a *strongly unambiguous graph* or a *mangrove*) is a DAG in which there is at most one directed path between any two vertices.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Equivalently, it is a DAG in which the subgraph reachable from any vertex induces an undirected tree.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A *polytree* (also called a *directed tree*) is a multitree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] An *arborescence* is a polytree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree away from a particular vertex, called the *root* of the arborescence.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Topological sorting is the algorithmic problem of finding a topological ordering of a given DAG.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Kahn's algorithm for topological sorting builds the vertex ordering directly.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] It maintains a list of vertices that have no incoming edges from other vertices that have not already been included in the partially constructed topological ordering; initially this list consists of the vertices with no incoming edges at all.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Then, it repeatedly adds one vertex from this list to the end of the partially constructed topological ordering, and checks whether its neighbors should be added to the list.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The algorithm terminates when all vertices have been processed in this way.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, a topological ordering may be constructed by reversing a postorder numbering of a depth-first search graph traversal.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Any undirected graph may be made into a DAG by choosing a total order for its vertices and directing every edge from the earlier endpoint in the order to the later endpoint.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The resulting orientation of the edges is called an acyclic orientation.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Different total orders may lead to the same acyclic orientation, so an n-vertex graph can have fewer than *n*! acyclic orientations.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The number of acyclic orientations is equal to |*χ*(−1)|, where χ is the chromatic polynomial of the given graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Any directed graph may be made into a DAG by removing a feedback vertex set or a feedback arc set, a set of vertices or edges (respectively) that touches all cycles.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] However, the smallest such set is NP-hard to find.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] An arbitrary directed graph may also be transformed into a DAG, called its condensation, by contracting each of its strongly connected components into a single supervertex.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] When the graph is already acyclic, its smallest feedback vertex sets and feedback arc sets are empty, and its condensation is the graph itself.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a given DAG, with n vertices and m edges, may be constructed in time *O*(*mn*) by using either breadth-first search or depth-first search to test reachability from each vertex.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, it can be solved in time *O*(*n**ω*) where *ω* < 2.373 is the exponent for matrix multiplication algorithms; this is a theoretical improvement over the *O*(*mn*) bound for dense graphs.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In all of these transitive closure algorithms, it is possible to distinguish pairs of vertices that are reachable by at least one path of length two or more from pairs that can only be connected by a length-one path.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction consists of the edges that form length-one paths that are the only paths connecting their endpoints.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, the transitive reduction can be constructed in the same asymptotic time bounds as the transitive closure.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The closure problem takes as input a vertex-weighted directed acyclic graph and seeks the minimum (or maximum) weight of a closure – a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The problem may be formulated for directed graphs without the assumption of acyclicity, but with no greater generality, because in this case it is equivalent to the same problem on the condensation of the graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Some algorithms become simpler when used on DAGs instead of general graphs, based on the principle of topological ordering.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, it is possible to find shortest paths and longest paths from a given starting vertex in DAGs in linear time by processing the vertices in a topological order, and calculating the path length for each vertex to be the minimum or maximum length obtained via any of its incoming edges.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for arbitrary graphs the shortest path may require slower algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm or the Bellman–Ford algorithm, and longest paths in arbitrary graphs are NP-hard to find.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graph representations of partial orderings have many applications in scheduling for systems of tasks with ordering constraints.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] An important class of problems of this type concern collections of objects that need to be updated, such as the cells of a spreadsheet after one of the cells has been changed, or the object files of a piece of computer software after its source code has been changed.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, a dependency graph is a graph that has a vertex for each object to be updated, and an edge connecting two objects whenever one of them needs to be updated earlier than the other.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle in this graph is called a circular dependency, and is generally not allowed, because there would be no way to consistently schedule the tasks involved in the cycle.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependency graphs without circular dependencies form DAGs.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, when one cell of a spreadsheet changes, it is necessary to recalculate the values of other cells that depend directly or indirectly on the changed cell.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] For this problem, the tasks to be scheduled are the recalculations of the values of individual cells of the spreadsheet.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependencies arise when an expression in one cell uses a value from another cell.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In such a case, the value that is used must be recalculated earlier than the expression that uses it.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Topologically ordering the dependency graph, and using this topological order to schedule the cell updates, allows the whole spreadsheet to be updated with only a single evaluation per cell.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Similar problems of task ordering arise in makefiles for program compilation and instruction scheduling for low-level computer program optimization.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A somewhat different DAG-based formulation of scheduling constraints is used by the program evaluation and review technique (PERT), a method for management of large human projects that was one of the first applications of DAGs.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In this method, the vertices of a DAG represent milestones of a project rather than specific tasks to be performed.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Instead, a task or activity is represented by an edge of a DAG, connecting two milestones that mark the beginning and completion of the task.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Each such edge is labeled with an estimate for the amount of time that it will take a team of workers to perform the task.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The longest path in this DAG represents the critical path of the project, the one that controls the total time for the project.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Individual milestones can be scheduled according to the lengths of the longest paths ending at their vertices.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph may be used to represent a network of processing elements.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In this representation, data enters a processing element through its incoming edges and leaves the element through its outgoing edges.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, in electronic circuit design, static combinational logic blocks can be represented as an acyclic system of logic gates that computes a function of an input, where the input and output of the function are represented as individual bits.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, the output of these blocks cannot be used as the input unless it is captured by a register or state element which maintains its acyclic properties.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuit schematics either on paper or in a database are a form of directed acyclic graphs using instances or components to form a directed reference to a lower level component.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuits themselves are not necessarily acyclic or directed.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Dataflow programming languages describe systems of operations on data streams, and the connections between the outputs of some operations and the inputs of others.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] These languages can be convenient for describing repetitive data processing tasks, in which the same acyclically-connected collection of operations is applied to many data items.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] They can be executed as a parallel algorithm in which each operation is performed by a parallel process as soon as another set of inputs becomes available to it.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In compilers, straight line code (that is, sequences of statements without loops or conditional branches) may be represented by a DAG describing the inputs and outputs of each of the arithmetic operations performed within the code.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] This representation allows the compiler to perform common subexpression elimination efficiently.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] At a higher level of code organization, the acyclic dependencies principle states that the dependencies between modules or components of a large software system should form a directed acyclic graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Feedforward neural networks are another example.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Graphs in which vertices represent events occurring at a definite time, and where the edges always point from an earlier time vertex to a later time vertex, are necessarily directed and acyclic.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The lack of a cycle follows because the time associated with a vertex always increases as you follow any directed path in the graph, so you can never return to a vertex on a path.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] This reflects our natural intuition that causality means events can only affect the future, they never affect the past, and thus we have no causal loops.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] An example of this type of directed acyclic graph are those encountered in the causal set approach to quantum gravity though in this case the graphs considered are transitively complete.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In the version history example below, each version of the software is associated with a unique time, typically the time the version was saved, committed or released.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In the citation graph examples below, the documents are published at one time and can only refer to older documents.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Sometimes events are not associated with a specific physical time.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Provided that pairs of events have a purely causal relationship, that is edges represent causal relations between the events, we will have a directed acyclic graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, a Bayesian network represents a system of probabilistic events as vertices in a directed acyclic graph, in which the likelihood of an event may be calculated from the likelihoods of its predecessors in the DAG.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, the moral graph of a DAG is the undirected graph created by adding an (undirected) edge between all parents of the same vertex (sometimes called *marrying*), and then replacing all directed edges by undirected edges.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Another type of graph with a similar causal structure is an influence diagram, the vertices of which represent either decisions to be made or unknown information, and the edges of which represent causal influences from one vertex to another.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In epidemiology, for instance, these diagrams are often used to estimate the expected value of different choices for intervention.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] That is in any application represented by a directed acyclic graph there is a causal structure, either an explicit order or time in the example or an order which can be derived from graph structure.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] This follows because all directed acyclic graphs have a topological ordering, i.e. there is at least one way to put the vertices in an order such that all edges point in the same direction along that order.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Family trees may be seen as directed acyclic graphs, with a vertex for each family member and an edge for each parent-child relationship.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Despite the name, these graphs are not necessarily trees because of the possibility of marriages between relatives (so a child has a common ancestor on both the mother's and father's side) causing pedigree collapse.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The graphs of matrilineal descent (mother-daughter relationships) and patrilineal descent (father-son relationships) are trees within this graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Because no one can become their own ancestor, family trees are acyclic.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The version history of a distributed revision control system, such as Git, generally has the structure of a directed acyclic graph, in which there is a vertex for each revision and an edge connecting pairs of revisions that were directly derived from each other.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] These are not trees in general due to merges.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In many randomized algorithms in computational geometry, the algorithm maintains a *history DAG* representing the version history of a geometric structure over the course of a sequence of changes to the structure.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance in a randomized incremental algorithm for Delaunay triangulation, the triangulation changes by replacing one triangle by three smaller triangles when each point is added, and by "flip" operations that replace pairs of triangles by a different pair of triangles.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The history DAG for this algorithm has a vertex for each triangle constructed as part of the algorithm, and edges from each triangle to the two or three other triangles that replace it.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] This structure allows point location queries to be answered efficiently: to find the location of a query point q in the Delaunay triangulation, follow a path in the history DAG, at each step moving to the replacement triangle that contains q.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The final triangle reached in this path must be the Delaunay triangle that contains q.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In a citation graph the vertices are documents with a single publication date.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The edges represent the citations from the bibliography of one document to other necessarily earlier documents.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The classic example comes from the citations between academic papers as pointed out in the 1965 article "Networks of Scientific Papers" by Derek J. de Solla Price who went on to produce the first model of a citation network, the Price model.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In this case the citation count of a paper is just the in-degree of the corresponding vertex of the citation network.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] This is an important measure in citation analysis.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Court judgements provide another example as judges support their conclusions in one case by recalling other earlier decisions made in previous cases.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A final example is provided by patents which must refer to earlier prior art, earlier patents which are relevant to the current patent claim.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] By taking the special properties of directed acyclic graphs into account, one can analyse citation networks with techniques not available when analysing the general graphs considered in many studies using network analysis.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance transitive reduction gives new insights into the citation distributions found in different applications highlighting clear differences in the mechanisms creating citations networks in different contexts.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Another technique is main path analysis, which traces the citation links and suggests the most significant citation chains in a given citation graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The Price model is too simple to be a realistic model of a citation network but it is simple enough to allow for analytic solutions for some of its properties.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Many of these can be found by using results derived from the undirected version of the Price model, the Barabási–Albert model.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] However, since Price's model gives a directed acyclic graph, it is a useful model when looking for analytic calculations of properties unique to directed acyclic graphs.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, the length of the longest path, from the n-th node added to the network to the first node in the network, scales as $\ln(n)$ .
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs may also be used as a compact representation of a collection of sequences.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In this type of application, one finds a DAG in which the paths form the given sequences.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] When many of the sequences share the same subsequences, these shared subsequences can be represented by a shared part of the DAG, allowing the representation to use less space than it would take to list out all of the sequences separately.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, the directed acyclic word graph is a data structure in computer science formed by a directed acyclic graph with a single source and with edges labeled by letters or symbols; the paths from the source to the sinks in this graph represent a set of strings, such as English words.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Any set of sequences can be represented as paths in a tree, by forming a tree vertex for every prefix of a sequence and making the parent of one of these vertices represent the sequence with one fewer element; the tree formed in this way for a set of strings is called a trie.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Similarly, a binary search tree can be viewed as a rooted DAG where paths represent sorted orderings of keys, though it lacks the path-merging compression found in more complex DAGs.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic word graph saves space over a trie by allowing paths to diverge and rejoin, so that a set of words with the same possible suffixes can be represented by a single tree vertex.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The same idea of using a DAG to represent a family of paths occurs in the binary decision diagram, a DAG-based data structure for representing binary functions.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] In a binary decision diagram, each non-sink vertex is labeled by the name of a binary variable, and each sink and each edge is labeled by a 0 or 1.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] The function value for any truth assignment to the variables is the value at the sink found by following a path, starting from the single source vertex, that at each non-sink vertex follows the outgoing edge labeled with the value of that vertex's variable.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/directed-acyclic-graph] Just as directed acyclic word graphs can be viewed as a compressed form of tries, binary decision diagrams can be viewed as compressed forms of decision trees that save space by allowing paths to rejoin when they agree on the results of all remaining decisions.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] In computer science, a **topological sort** or **topological ordering** of a directed graph is a linear ordering of its vertices such that for every directed edge *(u,v)* from vertex *u* to vertex *v*, *u* comes before *v* in the ordering.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] For instance, the vertices of the graph may represent tasks to be performed, and the edges may represent constraints that one task must be performed before another; in this application, a topological ordering is just a valid sequence for the tasks.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Precisely, a topological sort is a graph traversal in which each node *v* is visited only after all its dependencies are visited*.* A topological ordering is possible if and only if the graph has no directed cycles, that is, if it is a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Any DAG has at least one topological ordering, and there are linear time algorithms for constructing it.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Topological sorting has many applications, especially in ranking problems such as feedback arc set.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Topological sorting is also possible when the DAG has disconnected components.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] The canonical application of topological sorting is in scheduling a sequence of jobs or tasks based on their dependencies.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] The jobs are represented by vertices, and there is an edge from *x* to *y* if job *x* must be completed before job *y* can be started (for example, when washing clothes, the washing machine must finish before we put the clothes in the dryer).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Then, a topological sort gives an order in which to perform the jobs.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] A closely related application of topological sorting algorithms was first studied in the early 1960s in the context of the PERT technique for scheduling in project management.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] In this application, the vertices of a graph represent the milestones of a project, and the edges represent tasks that must be performed between one milestone and another.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Topological sorting forms the basis of linear-time algorithms for finding the critical path of the project, a sequence of milestones and tasks that controls the length of the overall project schedule.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] It is also used to decide in which order to load tables with foreign keys in databases.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] One of these algorithms, first described by Kahn (1962), works by choosing vertices in the same order as the eventual topological sort.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] First, find a list of "start nodes" that have no incoming edges and insert them into a set S; at least one such node must exist in a non-empty (finite) acyclic graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] If the graph is a DAG, a solution will be contained in the list L (although the solution is not necessarily unique).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Otherwise, the graph must have at least one cycle and therefore a topological sort is impossible.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Reflecting the non-uniqueness of the resulting sort, the structure S can be simply a set or a queue or a stack.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Depending on the order that nodes n are removed from set S, a different solution is created.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] A variation of Kahn's algorithm that breaks ties lexicographically forms a key component of the Coffman–Graham algorithm for parallel scheduling and layered graph drawing.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] An alternative algorithm for topological sorting is based on depth-first search.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Each node *n* gets *prepended* to the output list L only after considering all other nodes that depend on *n* (all descendants of *n* in the graph).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Since each edge and node is visited once, the algorithm runs in linear time.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] This depth-first-search-based algorithm is the one described by Cormen et al.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] (2001); it seems to have been first described in print by Tarjan in 1976.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] On a parallel random-access machine, a topological ordering can be constructed in *O*((log *n*)2) time using a polynomial number of processors, putting the problem into the complexity class **NC2**.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] One method for doing this is to repeatedly square the adjacency matrix of the given graph, logarithmically many times, using min-plus matrix multiplication with maximization in place of minimization.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] The resulting matrix describes the longest path distances in the graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Sorting the vertices by the lengths of their longest incoming paths produces a topological ordering.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] An algorithm for parallel topological sorting on distributed memory machines parallelizes the algorithm of Kahn for a DAG $G=(V,E)$ .
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] On a high level, the algorithm of Kahn repeatedly removes the vertices of indegree 0 and adds them to the topological sorting in the order in which they were removed.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Since the outgoing edges of the removed vertices are also removed, there will be a new set of vertices of indegree 0, where the procedure is repeated until no vertices are left.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] This algorithm performs $D+1$ iterations, where D is the longest path in G.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Each iteration can be parallelized, which is the idea of the following algorithm.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] In the following, it is assumed that the graph partition is stored on p processing elements (PE), which are labeled $0,\dots ,p-1$ .
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Each PE i initializes a set of local vertices $Q_{i}^{1}$ with indegree 0, where the upper index represents the current iteration.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Since all vertices in the local sets $Q_{0}^{1},\dots ,Q_{p-1}^{1}$ have indegree 0, i.e., they are not adjacent, they can be given in an arbitrary order for a valid topological sorting.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] To assign a global index to each vertex, a prefix sum is calculated over the sizes of $Q_{0}^{1},\dots ,Q_{p-1}^{1}$ .
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] So, each step, there are ${\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{p-1}|Q_{i}|}$ vertices added to the topological sorting.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] These vertices in $Q_{j}^{1}$ are removed, together with their corresponding outgoing edges.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] For each outgoing edge $(u,v)$ with endpoint v in another PE $l,j\neq l$ , the message $(u,v)$ is posted to PE l.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] After all vertices in $Q_{j}^{1}$ are removed, the posted messages are sent to their corresponding PE.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Each message $(u,v)$ received updates the indegree of the local vertex v.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] If the indegree drops to zero, v is added to $Q_{j}^{2}$ .
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] This procedure repeats until there are no vertices left to process, hence ${\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{p-1}|Q_{i}^{D+1}|=0}$ .
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Below is a high level, single program, multiple data pseudo-code overview of this algorithm.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] The communication cost depends heavily on the given graph partition.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] As for runtime, on a CRCW-PRAM model that allows fetch-and-decrement in constant time, this algorithm runs in ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({\frac {m+n}{p}}+D(\Delta +\log n)\right)}$ , where D is again the longest path in G and Δ the maximum degree.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] The topological ordering can also be used to quickly compute shortest paths through a weighted directed acyclic graph.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Let V be the list of vertices in such a graph, in topological order.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] On a graph of n vertices and m edges, this algorithm takes Θ(*n* + *m*), i.e., linear, time.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] If a topological sort has the property that all pairs of consecutive vertices in the sorted order are connected by edges, then these edges form a directed Hamiltonian path in the DAG.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] If a Hamiltonian path exists, the topological sort order is unique; no other order respects the edges of the path.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Conversely, if a topological sort does not form a Hamiltonian path, the DAG will have two or more valid topological orderings, for in this case it is always possible to form a second valid ordering by swapping two consecutive vertices that are not connected by an edge to each other.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Therefore, it is possible to test in linear time whether a unique ordering exists, and whether a Hamiltonian path exists, despite the NP-hardness of the Hamiltonian path problem for more general directed graphs (i.e., cyclic directed graphs).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Topological orderings are also closely related to the concept of a linear extension of a partial order in mathematics.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] A partially ordered set is just a set of objects together with a definition of the "≤" inequality relation, satisfying the axioms of reflexivity (*x* ≤ *x*), antisymmetry (if *x* ≤ *y* and *y* ≤ *x* then *x* = *y*) and transitivity (if *x* ≤ *y* and *y* ≤ *z*, then *x* ≤ *z*).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] A total order is a partial order in which, for every two objects *x* and *y* in the set, either *x* ≤ *y* or *y* ≤ *x*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Total orders are familiar in computer science as the comparison operators needed to perform comparison sorting algorithms.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] For finite sets, total orders may be identified with linear sequences of objects, where the "≤" relation is true whenever the first object precedes the second object in the order; a comparison sorting algorithm may be used to convert a total order into a sequence in this way.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] A linear extension of a partial order is a total order that is compatible with it, in the sense that, if *x* ≤ *y* in the partial order, then *x* ≤ *y* in the total order as well.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] One can define a partial ordering from any DAG by letting the set of objects be the vertices of the DAG, and defining *x* ≤ *y* to be true, for any two vertices *x* and *y*, whenever there exists a directed path from *x* to *y*; that is, whenever *y* is reachable from *x*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] With these definitions, a topological ordering of the DAG is the same thing as a linear extension of this partial order.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Conversely, any partial ordering may be defined as the reachability relation in a DAG.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] One way of doing this is to define a DAG that has a vertex for every object in the partially ordered set, and an edge *xy* for every pair of objects for which *x* ≤ *y*.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] An alternative way of doing this is to use the transitive reduction of the partial ordering; in general, this produces DAGs with fewer edges, but the reachability relation in these DAGs is still the same partial order.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] By using these constructions, one can use topological ordering algorithms to find linear extensions of partial orders.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] By definition, the solution of a scheduling problem that includes a precedence graph is a valid solution to topological sort (irrespective of the number of machines), however, topological sort in itself is *not* enough to optimally solve a scheduling optimisation problem.
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Hu's algorithm is a popular method used to solve scheduling problems that require a precedence graph and involve processing times (where the goal is to minimise the largest completion time amongst all the jobs).
[src:topological-sort-algorithm/kahn-s-algorithm] Like topological sort, Hu's algorithm is not unique and can be solved using DFS (by finding the largest path length and then assigning the jobs).
